<html><title>Bowen v American Hospital Association: Dissent #2</title>
<body bgcolor=#c0c0ff>
<h1>Bowen v American Hospital Association: Dissent #2</h1>
<hr>
<a href="bowen-s.htm">Syllabus</a> |
<a href="bowen-o.htm">Opinion</a> |
<a href="bowen-c.htm">Concur</a> |
<a href="bowen-d.htm">Dissent #1</a> |
<!a href="bowen-d2.htm">Dissent #2</a><p>

Return to <a href="comenu.htm">Court Decisions</a> |
<a href="../index.html">Ohio Right to Life Home</a><br>
<hr>

Justice O'CONNOR, dissenting.<p>

I fully agree with Justice WHITE's conclusion that the only question properly
before us is whether the Court of Appeals
correctly concluded that the Secretary has
no power under 29 U.S.C.  794 to regulate
medical treatment decisions concerning
handicapped newborn infants. I also agree
that application of established principles of
statutory construction and of the appropriate standard for judicial
review of agency action leads inescapably to the conclusion that the
Secretary has the authority to
regulate in this area. Because, however, I
see no need at this juncture to address the
details of the regulations or to assess
whether they are sufficiently rational to
survive review under 6 U.S.C.  706(2)(A), I
join only parts I, II, IV, and V of Justice
WHITE's dissent.<p>

