<html><title>Scott v Sandford: Concur #3</title>
<h1>Scott v Sandford: Concur #3</h1>
<hr>
<a href="scott-s.htm">Syllabus</a> |
<a href="scott-p.htm">Pleadings</a> |
<a href="scott-o.htm">Opinion</a> |
<a href="scott-c.htm">Concur 1</a> |
<a href="scott-c2.htm">Concur 2</a> |
<!a href="scott-c3.htm">Concur 3</a> |
<a href="scott-d.htm">Dissent </a><p>

Return to <a href="comenu.htm">Court decisions</a> |
<a href="../index.html">Ohio Right to Life Home</a>
<hr>

Mr. Justice Grier:<p>

I concur in the opinion delivered by Sir. Justice 
Nelson on the questions discussed by him.<p>

I also concur with the opinion of the court as 
delivered by the Chief Justice, that the Act of 
Congres of 6th March, 1820, is unconstitutional and void; and that, assuming
the facts as stated in 
the opinion, the plaintiff cannot sue as a citizen of 
Missouri in the courts of the United States. But, 
that the record shows a prima facie case of 
jurisdiction, requiring the court to decide all the 
questions properly arising in it; and as the 
decision of the pleas in bar shows that the 
plaintiff is a slave, and therefore not entitled 
to sue in a court of the United States, the form of 
the judgment is of little importantance; for whether the 
judgment be affirmed or dismissed for want of 
jurisdiction, it is justified by the decision of the 
court, and is the same in effect between the 
parties to the suit.<p>

