<html><title>Life-Issue Votes in the Senate</title>
<h1>Life-Issue Votes in the Senate</h1>
<hr>
Return to <a href="politics.htm">Politics</a> |
<a href="../index.html">Ohio Right to Life Home</a>
<hr>

This page shows how members of the U.S. Senate voted on
life-issue bills. Senators are grouped by state.<p>

Each vote is identified by an abbreviation at the top of
the column. The abbreviations are repeated at the beginning of each state.
These are linked to a brief description of the bill at the top of the page.
Each senator's vote is identifed as "L" for a pro-life vote, "C" for a
"pro-choice" vote, and "-" for absent, not voting, or voting "present".<p>

<font size=-1>
Disclaimers:<p>

One should be cautious about drawing conclusions from a single vote.
A senator may agree with the general idea of a bill but vote against it
because of objections to details;
in a few cases the exact effect of a bill is debatable; etc. Rather, we suggest
you look at an overall voting pattern.<p>

This information is presented for educational purposes only. We are not
advocating the election or defeat of any candidate.<p>
</font>

<hr>
<b>HF:</b> Henry Foster: Clinton's nominee for Surgeon General not only
supported abortion but had personally performed abortions (though he gave
varying numbers of how many at different times). The Senate voted 57 to 43 to
end a filibuster against Mr Foster's nomination, but this was insufficient as a
3/5 majority is required, so he was effectively rejected.<p>

<b>FI:</b> Federal Insurance: In 1993, at President Clinton's orders, the
health insurance of federal government employees began covering abortions. A
measure to prohibit federally-subsidized insurance programs from covering
abortion except in cases of life of the mother, rape, or incest, passed the
Senate 50 to 44.<p>

<b>PB:</b>
The Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act passed 54 to
44. Would ban abortions in which the unborn baby is partially delivered before
being killed. This bill was inspired by a procedure called
<a href="../aborters/dx.htm">"D&amp;X"</a>, "intact D&amp;E", and other
names.<p>
                                                                               
