<html><title>Life-Issue Votes in Congress</title>
<h1>Life-Issue Votes in Congress</h1>
<hr>
Return to <a href="politics.htm">Politics</a> |
<a href="../index.html">Ohio Right to Life Home</a>
<hr>

This page shows how members of the U.S. House of Representatives voted on
life-issue bills. Representatives are grouped by state.<p>

Each vote is identified by an abbreviation at the top of
the column. The abbreviations are repeated at the beginning of each state.
These are linked to a brief description of the bill at the top of the page.
Each representative's vote is identifed as "L" for a pro-life vote, "C" for a
"pro-choice" vote, and "-" for absent, not voting, or voting "present". (By
tradition, the Speaker usually does not vote.)<p>

<font size=-1>
Disclaimers:<p>

One should be cautious about drawing conclusions from a single vote.
A representative may agree with the general idea of a bill but vote against it
because of objections to details;
in a few cases the exact effect of a bill is debatable; etc. Rather, we suggest
you look at an overall voting pattern.<p>

This information is presented for educational purposes only. We are not
advocating the election or defeat of any candidate.<p>
</font>

<hr>

<b>TF:</b>
Tax-Payer Funded Abortions in Foreign Countries: A bill to deny federal tax
dollars to any organization that performs abortions, directly or indirectly, in
foreign countries (except when the life of the mother is at stake or in cases
of rape or incest). Passed 240 to 181.<p>

<b>TX:</b>
Title X: Current Title X regulations require participating clinics to "counsel"
pregnant women and girls about abortion as a "pregnancy management option".
Planned Parenthood, the nation's largest abortion provider, receives about $33
million per year through Title X. A proposal to completely eliminate Title X
and transfer its funds to health programs for poor people was defeated by 221
to 207.<p>

<b>AT:</b>
Abortion Training: An amendment to the Title X appropriations bill to remove a
provision that had been inserted in committee to say the government would not
discriminate against medical training programs that did not include abortion
training. This was in response to a decision by the Accreditation Council for
Graduate Medical Education that they would no longer recognize medical training
programs unless they included abortion training. The federal government has
long relied on ACGME accreditation as a condition for receiving various
government assistance. Pro-life provision survived by a vote of 235 to 189 on
August 3.<p>

<b>MC:</b>
Military Clinics: An amendment to the defense appropriations bill to prohibit
abortions at military clinics except when necessary to save the life of the
mother. Passed 226 to 191 on Septermber 7.<p>

<b>PB:</b>
The Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act (HR 1833), November 1, passed 288 to
139. Would ban abortions in which the unborn baby is partially delivered before
being killed. This bill was inspired by a procedure called
<a href="../aborters/dx.htm">"D&amp;X"</a>, "intact D&amp;E", and other
names.<p>

