<html><title>NARAL Exposes Bob Dole</title>
<body bgcolor=#c0c0ff>
<h1>NARAL Exposes Bob Dole</h1>
<hr>
Return to <a href="politics.htm">Politics</a> |
<a href="../index.html">Ohio Right to Life Home</a><br>
<hr>

The National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League is probably the
leading pro-abortion political organization in the country. (Not
counting the Supreme Court, which is nominally non-political.)
Earlier this year, NARRAL issued a press
release on Bob Dole. The first sentence read:

<blockquote>
Senator Bob Dole has cast 113 votes on abortion and
reproductive rights in his Senate career.  Of that number, 107 were
anti-choice votes.
</blockquote>

They go on to state that some of Senator Dole's most outrageous acts
include:

<ul>
<li>"Dole opposed a motion to table an amendment that would have put
Congress on record as stating that 'human life begins at conception.'"


<li>"Dole voted to support Senator Hatch's
constitutional amendment that would have permitted Congress and the
states to outlaw abortions."

<li>"Dole co-sponsored a bill to ban certain late-term abortion procedures, 
[partial birth aborttion] which presents a direct constitutional challenge
to Roe v. Wade."

<li>"Dole voted against the nomination of
Joycelyn Elders to be Surgeon General." (Elders nonetheless passed, though
she was later forced to resign amidst a flurry of controversies,
such as her chiding pro-lifers for having a "love affair with the
fetus", revelations that she concealed the fact that
condoms distributed to school children under one of her programs
were defective because she didn't want to harm public confidence
in the program, and her public call for legalization of drug abuse.)

<li>"Dole opposed the nomination of Dr. Henry Foster to be Surgeon General
and voted to prevent a vote on his nomination." (Foster was proud of
his record of not only defending abortion but having personally performed
abortions.)

</ul>

Some pro-lifers were disturbed by the fact that Dole voted for an early
version of the Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act, which restricts
anti-abortion protests and demonstrations. NARRAL explained that
pro-choicers should not take any comfort in this vote, pointing out that
he voted <i>against</i> the final bill.<p>

Indeed, according to NARRAL, Dole practically invented abortion as
a political issue. They quote him as telling a Christian Coalition
audience in South Carolina,

<blockquote>
Now let me make one thing clear. I have a flawless record of protecting
the unborn, and  thats not going to change when I become President of
the United States. I voted for it every year.  In fact, the first time this issue was an
issue was in my race in Kansas back in 1974: Think back about it -- go
back and look at the record, and youll find that when abortion first
became a national issue was at my re-election in 1974.
</blockquote>

Speaking of his 1974 election, NARRAL held a press conference
specifically to expose Dole's conduct in that race.<p>

According to NARRAL, Dole used some dirty tricks in that campaign
to defeat opponent Dr William Roy. Dole told voters that Roy supported
abortion, and indeed that Roy had personally performed abortions. These
charges apparently contributed to Roy's defeat.<p>

At the press conference, a reporter asked Mr Roy if he had,
in fact, ever perform an abortion. Roy replied that he had performed
a number of abortions. NARRAL's press release praises Mr Roy
for "having performed abortions ... in his ob/gyn medical practice."<p>

So to clarify, Dole's dirty campaign trick that NARRAL was exposing
was that he told people accurate information about where he and his
opponent stood on an important political issue, which, apparently,
his opponent would rather have kept secret from the voters.<p>

If I may be permitted an editorial comment, may I say that I am just
shocked at the low level that politics has reached today. Can you
imagine -- a politician sinking so low as to actually tell voters the
<b>truth</b>! It's a good
thing we have organizations like NARRAL to expose such dangerous
practices.<p>

<hr>
Sources:<p>

"NARAL Federal -- Republican Presidential Race Watch, Bob Dole",
<i>National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League</i>, 1996.<p>

"Statement of Kate Michelman at NARAL'S Press Conference on Abortion",
<i>National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League</i>, 1996.<p>

"Statement of Dr William Roy at NARAL'S Press Conference on Abortion",
<i>National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League</i>, 1996.<p>

