<html><title>Childrens' Defense Fund</title>
<h1>Childrens' Defense Fund</h1>

<hr>
Return to <a href="people.htm">People and Organizations</a> |
<a href="../index.html">Ohio Right to Life Home</a>
<hr>

The Childrens' Defense Fund (CDF) staged a massive "Stand for Children"
rally in Washington, DC, Saturday June 1, 1996 to pressure Congress to adopt
their policies.<p>

Among CDF policies which are presumably intended to defend children are
opposition to the proposed $500 per child tax credit and opposition to any
restrictions on abortion, including the ban on partial-birth abortions. The
Children's Defense Fund would not support efforts to make adoption easier, and
is leading the coalition against the proposed Parental Rights Act.<p>

Other organizations that joined CDF in the "Stand For Children" rally are
Planned Parenthood, the nation's leading provider of abortions; Zero Population
Growth, which is founded on the principle that there are already too many
people in the world so children are undesirable and dangerous; the
Drug Policy Foundation, which promotes legalization of drugs;
and the Gay and Lesbian Victory Fund and Human (Gay) Rights
Campaign, whose idea of "defending children" is somewhat unusual.<p>

CDF conducted an excellent marketing drive to sell this rally to more
mainstream organizations, like Big Brothers and church groups, many of
whom probably have little idea of the policies being pursued by the
organizers.<p>

<hr>
Adapted from an article in Right to Life of Cincinnati Newsletter, vol 26 no 6,
June/July 1996.<p>

