<html><title>Media E-Mail Addresses</title>
<body bgcolor=#ccccff>
<h1><img src="../mailbox.gif">Media E-Mail Addresses</h1>

<hr>
Return to <a href="people.htm">People and Organizations</a> |
<a href="../index.html">Ohio Right to Life Home</a><br>
<hr>

<a href="#disclaimers">Disclaimers</a><p>

<h2 align=center>Index</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="#Howto">Tips for Wise Use</a>
<li><a href="#Daily">Daily newspapers </a>
<li><a href="#Alt">Weekly/alternative newspapers</a>
<li><a href="#College">College newspapers</a>
<li><a href="#Magazines">Magazines</a>
<li><a href="#News">News/media services and press associations</a>
<li><a href="#Stations">Radio and TV stations</a>
<li><a href="#bbc">BBC Outlets</a>
<li><a href="#cbc">CBC Outlets</a>
<li><a href="#Computers">Computer publications</a>
<li><a href="#Publish">Publishing houses</a>
</ul><p>
<hr>

<a name="Howto"></a>
<h2>Tips for Wise Use</h2>

Properly used, E-mailed press releases or letters to the
editor can greatly increase your organization's effectiveness and voice in
religious and secular media.<p>

Proper etiquette indicates that editors be E-Mailed in advance with a
notice that you'd like to E-Mail a press release to them on occasion.<p>

When done in a professional manner, and not over-used, the practice of
E-Mailing press release can save both your organization and the editor of
the receiving publication a good deal of time in getting a PSA, press
release, or even a "Letter to the Editor" to press, as the information is
already on the editor's computer and ready to edit.<p>

Some important points to remember when using this list:

<ul>
<li>Do NOT send out a blanket news release to every media outlet on this list.
A bicycling magazine is unlikely to be
interested in your thoughts on abortion, no matter how cogent they are,
and all you're going to do is get some recipients very annoyed.

<li>Be sure to personalize the address on each e-mail, perhaps with some
some sort of  mail-merge program.
Generic E-mail messages will stand a good
chanceof being deleted by the editorial staff.

<li>If you want a publication to print your letter to the editor, news
release, etc, you'll need to include your postal address and phone
number for verification purposes.
</ul>

<hr>

<a name="Daily"></a>
<h2>Daily newspapers</h2>

<ul>
<li>Albany (N.Y.) Times-Union
  <ul>
  <li><a href="mailto:tuletters@aol.com">Letter to the Editor</a>
