<html><title>Why Anti-Abortion Demostrators Turn Violent</title>
<body bgcolor=#c0c0ff>
<h1>Why Anti-Abortion Demostrators Turn Violent</h1>
by Jennifer Florio<p>

<hr>
Return to <a href="racism.htm">Abortion and Race</a> |
<a href="../tangents/tangents.htm">Tangents</a> |
<a href="../index.html">Ohio Right to Life Home</a>
<hr>

In the late 1960s, a political scientist named Ted Robert Gurr wrote a
book entitled <i>Why Men
Rebel</i> (Princeton University Press, 1970). In this work, Gurr argued
essentially that people who choose
violent rebellion are led to do so when they experience what he termed
"relative deprivation". This
phenomena occurs when people perceive that there is something in life
which they a) deserve to obtain, b)
have seen other segments of society obtain, and c) feel that they
would be able to obtain were it not for the
blockage by their government or society of their efforts to achieve
their goal. These people also feel that
there is no other means of effectively changing the conditions of
their situation other than violent rebellion.
Although some sociologists found fault with Gurr's work because of his
inability to document the point at
which the sociological phenomena of relative deprivation was
transferred into the choice to utilize a
political means of solution (i.e. political will), I believe that
Gurr's hypotheses were correct. People
become angry when they see that their ability to function as full
members of society is being held captive
by others. If they do not possess any other outlet for correcting this
situation, they resort to violence.<p>

Although the first social condition which we may think of as being a
prime target for change
through violence is lack of economic opportunity, I would posit that
another likely point of frustration for
individuals which may lead them to violent action is the lack of a
political voice. People who live in
poverty can blame their circumstances at least partially on ambiguous
economic factors that seem to be
beyond the control of any particular person or segment of society.
However, when a group of people has
organized as a political entity and attempted to impact society with
their message but are denied the ability
to do so by the opposing political powers, cultural establishment, or
media of the society in which they
live, they may experience relative deprivation and feel that the only
means by which they may hope to
obtain a political voice is through violence.<p>

It is a fact that the American cultural establishment, government, and
media have attempted to
deprive the pro-life movement of a voice. Hollywood actors and
producers have made a number of films
for television that are extremely sympathetic to the pro-abortion
cause. The Madison Avenue fashion
industry has also given of its resources to the pro-abortion cause,
such as a late 1980s ad for Esprit
clothing that suggested we "keep abortion legal unless George Bush is
available to babysit". The U.S.
government has also done its share to heap favor upon the
pro-abortionists by applying the same laws
which it used to stop violence by the Ku Klux Klan and to prosecute
Mafia bosses to pro-life
demonstrators, effectively lumping those who feel that abortion is
wrong into the same moral categories as
racists and criminals. Further, newspaper and television media have
given biased friendly coverage to the
pro-abortion establishment, while failing to investigate the
sometimes-deadly medical malpractice at clinics
or to mention any of the work done by pro-lifers to economically and
emotionally support women who
choose to keep their unplanned babies.<p>

Are those anti-abortion activists who turn to violence justified? No.
Although they have correctly
perceived the attempts by the establishment cultural, political, and
media entities to deny the pro-life
movement a political voice and they may be extremely frustrated by the
overwhelming bigotry on the part
of these groups, those who turn to violence are wrong. Violence is not
our only option. In spite of the
clear attempt to deny our political voice on the part of these
societal forces, the pro-life movement is
finding ways around that blockage. Pro-lifers continue to demonstrate
at clinics in spite of restrictions.
We have established what amounts to an alternative, "underground"
press system with newsletters and
<a href="../links.htm">computer web-sites</a>.
We host speakers anywhere we can -- in schools,
churches, and at civic meetings -- to
get our message across in spite of the media black-out on our positive
activities. Pro-life members of the
artistic community have lent their talents to us for use on billboards
and bumper stickers, and those with
financial resources, such as the Arthur DeMoss Foundation, are
presenting the pro-life message in paid
media advertisements. In spite of an orchestrated, well-funded, and
pervasive effort to deny us an
opportunity to articulate our beliefs, the establishment has failed.
We will continue to have a voice, and
we will do so without violence.<p>

<hr>
Return to <a href="racism.htm">Abortion and Race</a> |
<a href="../tangents/tangents.htm">Tangents</a> |
<a href="../index.html">Ohio Right to Life Home</a><p>

