	<!-- TOC text goes here -->
<IMG WIDTH=149 HEIGHT=236 SRC=bcover.gif ALT=Cover ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=8 VSPACE=3>

<STRONG>The Moral Question of Abortion</STRONG> by Stephen Schwarz is a significant work of philosophical reflection upon the absolute value of human life. Tightly argued from firm rational foundations, this book can be used to articulate an anti-abortion apologia as well as to inspire those in the trenches and at the barricades of the conflict.  The book also includes a number of photographs that dramatically show the humanness of the fetus. This is an informative resource for anyone concerned about the abortion issue.<P>

<STRONG><EM>About the author:</EM></STRONG><BR>
Stephen Schwarz received his Ph.D. from Harvard University.  He is currently Professor of Philosophy at the University of Rhode Island.

<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR WIDTH=90%>

<TABLE WIDTH=560 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=20 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=57% VALIGN=TOP>
<FONT SIZE=-1>
<EM>"I unhesitatingly recommend this book as an indespensable Baedeker through the tortured landscape of the abortion wars. It should be read by every thinking, morally responsible citizen in the country."</EM>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>- From the foreword by <STRONG>Bernard N. Nathanson, M.D.</STRONG><P ALIGN=LEFT>

<HR WIDTH=30%>

<EM>"This book does what no other book I know does: carefully and fairly faces and answers every one of the philosophical arguments that have been given to justify abortion. Although hundreds of books on the subject of abortion have appeared, none of them is as thorough as this one."</EM>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT><STRONG>- Dr. Peter Kreeft</STRONG><BR>
Professor of Philosophy, Boston College
</TD>

<TD VALIGN=TOP>
<FONT SIZE=-1>
<EM>"I predict that this book will soon become the one indispensable sourcebook for the abortion debate. Well written, it can be understood by the front-line troops on either side, but it is profound and thorough enough to give pause to the highest legal and philosophical minds. It appeals to no religious faith, only to reason. It magnificently sorts out and identifies most of the greatest confusions in the present abortion debates.... This book is must-reading for everyone."</EM>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT><STRONG>- Dr. William A. Marra</STRONG><BR>
Professor of Philosophy, Fordham University<P ALIGN=LEFT>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

