<!-- End Chapter Bar -->

</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>

	<!-- Text Body -->
	<TABLE BGCOLOR=White WIDTH=620 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0 BORDER=0>
	<TR>
	<TD WIDTH=50 BGCOLOR=669999>
	<FONT COLOR=669999>
	.
	</FONT>
</TD>

<TD WIDTH=570 BGCOLOR=White>
	<TABLE BGCOLOR=FFFFFF CELLPADDING=15 CELLSPACING=0 BORDER=0>
	<TR><TD WIDTH=570>
	<!-- Section title -->
	<FONT COLOR=Black Size=3>
	<EM>
	Quickening
	</EM>
	<P>

	<!-- Body text goes here -->

Quickening refers to the time when the mother first feels the baby inside
   her, at approximately sixteen to seventeen weeks.  Quickening refers to
   the mother's perception of the baby's movements; it has nothing to do
   with the baby himself, who is there long before quickening.  In the very
   early phases of his existence he does not move, but he is there, and that
   is the important point.  Later he moves, but the mother cannot feel the
   movements; the important point is that he is there.  Dr. Liley states:<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE><FONT SIZE=-1>
        Historically "quickening" was supposed to delineate the time when the
        fetus became an independent human being possessed of a soul.  Now,
        however, we know that while he may have been too small to make his
        motions felt, the unborn baby is active and independent long before
        his mother feels him.  Quickening is a maternal sensitivity and
        depends on the mother's own fat, the position of the placenta and the
        size and strength of the unborn child.<SUP><A HREF=notes4.htm#10>10</A></SUP><P>
</FONT></BLOCKQUOTE>
	
	</FONT>
	<!-- End Body text -->

	<P>
	<A HREF=4-4.htm><IMG SRC=next.gif ALIGN=RIGHT></A>
	<FONT Size=1>
	Comments to <A HREF="mailto:life@infinet.com">life@infinet.com</A><BR>
	<A HREF=copy.htm>Copyright</A> &copy;1990 Stephen D. Schwarz<BR>
	Published by Loyola Press; used with permission<p>
	</FONT>
	</TD></TR>
	</TABLE>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!-- End Text Body -->

</TD></TR>
