<!-- End Chapter Bar -->

</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>

	<!-- Text Body -->
	<TABLE BGCOLOR=White WIDTH=620 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0 BORDER=0>
	<TR>
	<TD WIDTH=50 BGCOLOR=669999>
	<FONT COLOR=669999>
	.
	</FONT>
</TD>

<TD WIDTH=570 BGCOLOR=White>
	<TABLE BGCOLOR=FFFFFF CELLPADDING=15 CELLSPACING=0 BORDER=0>
	<TR><TD WIDTH=570>
	<!-- Section title -->
	<FONT COLOR=Black Size=3>
	<EM>
	Implantation
	</EM>
	<P>

	<!-- Body text goes here -->

About seven or eight days after conception, the tiny zygote implants in the
  wall of the uterus, after floating down the fallopian tube.  Nathanson, in
  <EM>Aborting America</EM>, suggested why implantation might be selected as the
   beginning of human life: "Biochemically, this is when alpha [the zygote]
   announces its presence as part of the human community by means of its
   hormonal messages, which we now have the technology to receive.  We
   also know biochemically that it is an independent organism distinct from
   the mother."<SUP><A HREF=notes4.htm#25>25</A></SUP><P>

        But clearly the time when a being announces its presence is not
   identical with the time when it comes into being.  It may already <EM>be</EM> before
   it is <EM>known</EM> or it may be and be known by one person and not another,
   or in one way and not another.
	
	</FONT>
	<!-- End Body text -->

	<P>
	<A HREF=4-10.htm><IMG SRC=next.gif ALIGN=RIGHT></A>
	<FONT Size=1>
